Perfect ðŸš€ Here are the main notes for your question:

ðŸ”¹ Next.js API Routes & CRUD Notes
1. What are API Routes in Next.js?

Next.js lets you create backend APIs inside the same project (no need for separate Express server).

You create files inside /pages/api/ â†’ each file becomes an API endpoint.

Runs only on the server-side (never exposed to client).

2. How Next.js Handles API Routes?

Any file inside /pages/api/ is treated as an API endpoint.

Export a default function (req, res) â†’ it handles the request.

Supports all HTTP methods: GET, POST, PUT, DELETE.

3. Simple CRUD API Example
ðŸ“‚ Folder structure:
pages/
 â””â”€â”€ api/
      â””â”€â”€ users.js

users.js
let users = [];

export default function handler(req, res) {
  if (req.method === "GET") {
    res.status(200).json(users); // Read
  } 
  else if (req.method === "POST") {
    const newUser = req.body;
    users.push(newUser); // Create
    res.status(201).json(newUser);
  } 
  else if (req.method === "PUT") {
    const { id, name } = req.body;
    users = users.map(u => (u.id === id ? { ...u, name } : u)); // Update
    res.status(200).json({ message: "User updated" });
  } 
  else if (req.method === "DELETE") {
    const { id } = req.body;
    users = users.filter(u => u.id !== id); // Delete
    res.status(200).json({ message: "User deleted" });
  } 
  else {
    res.setHeader("Allow", ["GET", "POST", "PUT", "DELETE"]);
    res.status(405).end(`Method ${req.method} Not Allowed`);
  }
}

4. Key Points to Remember

âœ… API routes run only on server â†’ safe for secrets.
âœ… Great for small projects, form submissions, authentication, etc.
âœ… For large apps, you might still use Express/Nest.js with Next.js.
âœ… req.body requires middleware like body-parser or Next.js built-in support for JSON.











ðŸ”¹ 1. Synchronous Code (Blocking code)

Matlab ek kaam khatam hone tak agla kaam ruk jaata hai.

Ek line execute hogi â†’ uske complete hone ke baad hi agla line chalega.

Node.js single-threaded hai, toh agar sync code mai koi heavy task (like file read, DB query) hogaya â†’ pura thread block ho jaata hai â†’ baaki requests ruk jaati hain.

ðŸ‘‰ Example:

const fs = require("fs");

// Sync file read
const data = fs.readFileSync("file.txt", "utf8");
console.log("File data:", data);

console.log("This will run after file read is done.");


âž¡ï¸ Agar file bada hai ya slow disk hai â†’ tab tak server freeze ho jaayega.

ðŸ”¹ 2. Asynchronous Code (Non-blocking code)

Matlab ek kaam background mai bhej diya jaata hai (event loop + callback queue handle karta hai).
Jab wo task complete hota hai â†’ callback ya promise resolve hota hai â†’ phir result milta hai.
Isse ek request dusre ko block nahi karti â†’ server multiple requests handle kar paata hai easily.

ðŸ‘‰ Example:
const fs = require("fs");
// Async file read
fs.readFile("file.txt", "utf8", (err, data) => {
  if (err) throw err;
  console.log("File data:", data);
});
console.log("This runs immediately without waiting for file read.");


âž¡ï¸ File read hone ka wait nahi karega, aage ka code turant execute karega.

ðŸ”¹ 3. Why is Async Important in Node.js?

Node.js ek hi thread mai chal raha hota hai (single-threaded event loop).
Agar sync (blocking) code likhoge â†’ ek hi request sabko rok degi â†’ server slow/laggy ho jaayega.
Async code se Node.js ek sath 1000s of requests handle kar paata hai â†’ fast, scalable server banta hai.
Yeh hi reason hai ki Node.js ko "non-blocking I/O" bola jaata hai.

ðŸ”¹ 4. Modern Async Handling

Callbacks (old way, callback hell problem).

Promises (better, .then() .catch()).

async/await (best, clean & readable).

ðŸ‘‰ Example with async/await:

const fs = require("fs").promises;

async function readFile() {
  try {
    const data = await fs.readFile("file.txt", "utf8");
    console.log("File data:", data);
  } catch (err) {
    console.error("Error:", err);
  }
}

readFile();
console.log("This still runs immediately, async handles file later.");


ðŸ“Œ TL;DR Notes

Sync = blocking (slow, sab ruk jaata hai).

Async = non-blocking (fast, scalable).

Node.js ke liye async important hai kyunki single-threaded hai.

Real-world mai hamesha async use karo (file read, DB queries, API calls, etc).


ðŸ“’ Express.js Notes
1. Express Kya Hai?

Express ek minimal & flexible Node.js framework hai.

Ye server-side web apps & APIs banana easy banata hai.

Node ke upar ek layer hai jo repetitive kaam simplify karti hai.

2. Node.js Server vs Express Server
ðŸŸ¢ Node.js (without Express)
const http = require("http");

const server = http.createServer((req, res) => {
  if (req.url === "/") {
    res.writeHead(200, { "Content-Type": "text/plain" });
    res.end("Hello from Node");
  }
});
server.listen(5000);


ðŸ‘‰ Problems:

Har route ke liye if-else

Request body parse manually

Middleware concept nahi

ðŸŸ¢ Express.js
const express = require("express");
const app = express();

app.get("/", (req, res) => res.send("Hello from Express"));
app.listen(5000);


ðŸ‘‰ Benefits:

Simple routing

Built-in middleware support

Easy to scale

3. Express Ke Features

Routing system (app.get, app.post, etc.)

Middleware (authentication, logging, error handling)

Request parsing (JSON, URL-encoded)

Static file serving

Ecosystem packages (JWT, session, CORS, etc.)

4. Express App Structure (Scalable Apps)
project/
â”‚â”€â”€ index.js          // entry point
â”‚â”€â”€ routes/           // URL definitions
â”‚â”€â”€ controllers/      // business logic
â”‚â”€â”€ middleware/       // auth, validation
â”‚â”€â”€ models/           // database models

5. Routes, Controllers & Middleware Example
âœ… index.js
const express = require("express");
const userRoutes = require("./routes/userRoutes");

const app = express();
app.use(express.json());

app.use("/api/users", userRoutes);

app.listen(5000, () => console.log("Server running on 5000"));

âœ… routes/userRoutes.js
const express = require("express");
const { getUsers } = require("../controllers/userController");
const { protect } = require("../middleware/authMiddleware");

const router = express.Router();

router.get("/", getUsers);
router.post("/", protect, (req, res) => res.send("User created"));

module.exports = router;

âœ… controllers/userController.js
const getUsers = (req, res) => {
  res.json({ message: "All users fetched" });
};
module.exports = { getUsers };

âœ… middleware/authMiddleware.js
const protect = (req, res, next) => {
  const token = req.headers.authorization;
  if (token === "secret123") next();
  else res.status(401).json({ message: "Unauthorized" });
};
module.exports = { protect };

6. Middleware Types

Application-level â†’ app.use(logger)

Router-level â†’ specific routes pe apply hota hai

Built-in â†’ express.json(), express.static()

Error-handling â†’ (err, req, res, next)

7. Why Express?

Node se server bana sakte hai, lekin:

Routing tough

Request parsing manual

Middleware support nahi

Express ye sab problems solve karta hai.

ðŸ‘‰ One-liner for interview:
"Express ek abstraction hai jo Node.js ko easy aur scalable banata hai by providing routing, middleware, and request handling features."
